<h1>Authoring Refinery pages in XML</h1>

<div id="top">
   <style scoped="">code, pre, kbd { font-family: monospace, serif;  font-size: 80%;  padding: 2px 4px;  color: #000;  background-color: #e0f5f5;  border-radius: 4px; }   kbd { background-color: #222; color: white; }  figcaption { font-style: italic;     color: #737373; margin-top: 0.3em; }   figure.site img { border: 2px solid #00a099; padding: 0.3em; } figure.image-wide img { width: 100%; height: auto; } figure img.narrow { max-width: 291px; height: auto; }</style>
   
   <div class="grid">
      <div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-two-thirds palm-one-whole">
         <p class="lead">This page describes an authoring framework for Refinery which is based on XML (eXtensible
            Markup Language).</p>
         <p>We have developed this new framework to help authors produce correctly-formatted pages.
            Our goal is to offer web pages which are both <strong>responsive</strong> and <strong>accessible</strong>. Responsive pages will display sensibly on any device, from a full-sized monitor
            down to a mobile phone. Accessible pages must be accessible to <em>all</em> users, including those who use screen readers, those with motor issues who cannot
            use a pointing device reliably, those with cognitive issues who need clear, concise
            content and a whole raft of other users who need special consideration. In order to
            achieve these design goals, we have a set of conventions for our HTML and CSS. Our
            XML application offers you a simple set of layout options, and then converts your
            marked-up document to correctly-formatted HTML and CSS. This is intended to make life
            easier both for you, the author, and for the proofreader who checks and approves your
            work.</p>
         <p>See <a href="#xml-software">XML-aware software</a> for guidance on which software to use to create your XML pages. We show you a <a href="#simple-example">simple example of a page authored in XML</a>. </p>
      </div>
