      <div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-two-thirds palm-one-whole" id="xml-software">
         <h2>XML-aware software</h2>
         <p>There are two types of editor which you can use to work with XML documents: <strong>WYSIWYG</strong> (“What You See Is What You Get”) and <strong>text editors</strong>. A WYSIWYG editor looks just like a word processor, in that the result is laid out
            nicely on the page — much as it is in Refinery’s default view of a page. With some
            WYSIWYG editors you can choose whether or not you see the actual XML markup: start-tags,
            end-tags and attributes. A text editor will show you the source XML, markup and all,
            but will attempt to make your life easier by using different colours (“syntax highlighting”)
            for tags, attribute values, and text. Which XML editors are available to you on your
            own machine will depend on the operating system it runs. WYSIWYG editors for XML are
            relatively rare, and can be pricey.</p>
         <p class="push-half--bottom">For our purposes, the features we require in an XML-aware editor are:</p>
         <ul>
            <li>checking that the XML is “well-formed”, i.e. that the XML syntax is correct, and telling
               you when it’s not</li>
            <li>helping you to ensure that the structure of the XML conforms to our rules for the
               allowed content of each page, i.e. that the XML is “valid”</li>
            <li>providing support for XSLT transforms. We use XSLT to convert your XML into the final
               HTML which will be pasted into Refinery</li>
         </ul>
         <p class="push-half--bottom">Here are some suggestions:</p>
         <ul>
            <li><strong>Notepad++</strong>: this is a free text editor, which supports XML authoring, validation against XML
               Schema, and XSLT transforms. Notepad++ is a Windows-only program. <a href="https://notepad-plus-plus.org/downloads/">Download Notepad++</a>
</li>
            <li><strong>XmlBlueprint</strong>: another text editor, not free, but with a strong XML pedigree. XmlBlueprint is a
               Windows-only program. <a href="https://www.xmlblueprint.com/download-xml-editor.htm">Download XmlBlueprint</a>
</li>
            <li><strong>xmplify</strong>: a text editor with support for DTD/Schema and XSLT. Xmplify runs on macOS systems.
               <a href="http://xmplifyapp.com/">Download Xmplify</a>
</li>
            <li><strong>xmlcopyeditor</strong>: a text editor with support for DTD/Schema and XSLT. XML Copy Editor runs on Linux
               — it installs happily on a Linux Mint machine. <a href="https://community.linuxmint.com/software/view/xmlcopyeditor">Download xmlcopyeditor</a>
</li>
            <li><strong>Oxygen</strong>: a premium WYSIWYG XML editor. Oxygen is multi-platform, and will run on Windows,
               macOS and Linux. Mentioned only for completeness (i.e. an example of WYSIWYG support)
               — it is very expensive and has a host of features which we will never need. <a href="https://www.oxygenxml.com/xml_editor/download_oxygenxml_editor.html">Download Oxygen</a>
</li>
         </ul>
      </div>
