         <h2>Creating a Refinery page with XML support</h2>
         <p>You create your new Refinery page in the usual manner from the main Refinery menu.
            Decide which existing page your new page will be a ‘child’ of, and give it a page
            title. You can save your page now, and come back to it in Refinery later, once you
            have created the page content using the XML system.</p>
         <p>Now open your chosen XML editing program and create a new XML document for your page.
            Associate it with the DTD or XML Schema we have created for Refinery documents. Your
            XML editor may fill in the basic structure for you: this is what XmlBlueprint does:</p>
         <figure class="site image-wide float--left push--right "><%= image_tag 'new-page-xmlblueprint.png?sha=ca27474a3ad4d08e', alt: 'screenshot showing a new document dialogue in XmlBlueprint' %><figcaption>Fig. 2: New record dialogue in XmlBlueprint, with the basic structure of the document
               already filled in</figcaption>
         </figure>
         <p>Author your page in the XML editor. It should help you by offering a list of valid
            elements when you start a new element, and by inserting end-tags to match each start-tag.</p>
         <p>Save the XML page, then run the XSLT transform <code>refinery-html.xsl</code> on it. Go to the transformed page, highlight the whole thing, and copy it (Ctrl-C
            on Windows).</p>
         <p>Go back to Refinery and ask to edit the page you created earlier. Open the HTML text
            box by pressing the ‘HTML’ button. If the page contains any HTML content, delete it
            all. Now paste (Ctrl-V on Windows) the HTML you just generated into the Refinery page.
            The rendered view will instantly update. Save the updated Refinery page. To see the
            page as it will appear on our web site, go to the main Refinery menu and press the
            ‘eye’ icon to the right of your page filename.</p>
         <h3 id="including-images">Including images in your page</h3>
         <p>Refinery has its own method of dealing with images. Before you can include images
            in your page, you have to upload them to Refinery. There is a separate menu for images:</p>
         <figure class="site image-wide float--left push--right "><%= image_tag 'refinery-image-menu.png?sha=7e5fe706907e8bb9', alt: 'refinery image menu' %><figcaption>Fig. 3: Refinery's image menu</figcaption>
         </figure>
         <p>Click on the “Add new image” button and complete the dialogue. When your image has
            been uploaded, it will appear in the images menu page. Below each image there is a
            row of buttons, similar to those provided for pages. Click on the right-hand button
            (which looks like an eye) to bring up the image in a separate browser tab. </p>
         <figure class="site image-wide float--left push--right "><%= image_tag 'view-image-button.png?sha=b09353a3ada97d45', alt: 'view image button' %><figcaption>Fig. 4: View image button</figcaption>
         </figure>
         <p>The address (URL) of the image will appear in the browser address bar. Copy this URL
            and paste it into the <span style="font-family: Courier, sans-serif;">image</span> src attribute. Delete the start of the URL so it begins ‘/system/images/’. The image
            should now appear both in Refinery’s preview and in the finished web page.</p>
         <h3 id="including-page-links">Links within the current page, and links to other pages</h3>
         <p>You can make a link to any part of the current page, using the pattern ‘#’ followed
            by the ID of the section you want to link to: <span style="font-family: Courier, sans-serif;"> &lt;a href="#mySection"&gt;My section&lt;/a&gt; </span>
</p>
         <p>To link to other pages generated by Refinery, you can use the “eye” button in Refinery’s
            Pages menu to see the page you want to link to. Its URL will be in the browser address
            bar. Copy this URL and paste it into the <em>href</em> attribute of your link. Delete the first part of the URL, so that it begins ‘/cms/’.
            (This is similar to the technique you use to include image URLs in your XML page.)</p>
      </div>
