         <h2>XML markup rules</h2>
         <p>The XML elements provided should allow you to mark up your pages so that they look
            right on our web site. This section explains the role of each XML element type in
            our application.</p>
         <h3 id="xml-page">Page</h3>
         <p>The <code>page</code> element surrounds the whole page. It must be the ‘root element’ of each page’s XML
            document, and must occur exactly once.</p>
         <h3 id="xml-title">Title</h3>
         <p>The <code>title</code> element contains the page title. This title is also entered in Refinery, but it is
            included here for your convenience (so you know which XML source relates to each Refinery
            page).</p>
         <h3 id="xml-section">Section</h3>
         <p>The <code>section</code> element contains a single section of your page. It must have an ID attribute, so
            that it can be linked to from the ‘table of contents’ which is generated by the XSLT
            transform.</p>
         <h3 id="xml-p">Paragraph</h3>
         <p>The <code>p</code> element contains a single paragraph.</p>
         <h3 id="xml-image">Image</h3>
         <p>The <code>image</code> element contains all the information required to display an image, together with
            alt text for screen readers and a caption to appear on the page. As described <a href="#including-images">above</a>, you have to upload each image to Refinery before you can include it in your page.
            Paste the URL assigned to the image by Refinery into the <em>src</em> attribute, removing the initial part of the URL so that it begins ‘/system/images/’.
            Now provide an <em>alt</em> text for screen readers, and a <em>caption</em> to appear beneath the image.</p>
      </div>
